Democrats blame President Trump for condoning 'acts of violence' in light of bombs mailed to Clintons, Obamas, CNN

By Chris Sommerfeldt
| New York Daily News |
Oct 24, 2018 | 4:55 PM
Skip

Democratic leaders didn’t buy President Trump’s call for calm Wednesday after bombs were mailed to a media organization and several of his political opponents, instead faulting him for fostering a climate in which violence has become the new normal.

“Trump’s words ring hollow until he reverses his statements that condone acts of violence,” Senate and House Minority Leaders Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.) and Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.) said in a joint statement.

The top Dems cited Trump’s recent public praise for a Republican congressman who pleaded guilty to assaulting a reporter; his refusal to unambiguously condemn white supremacy in the wake of Charlottesville; his encouraging supporters to rough up protesters at political rallies; his warm words for “dictators around the world;” and his repeated references to the free press as “the enemy of the people.”

“Time and time again, the President has condoned physical violence and divided Americans with his words and his actions,” the Democrats said.

A White House spokeswoman did not return a request for comment.

Earlier in the day, Trump had a rare kumbaya moment at the White House and called for the nation “to unify and come together” after rudimentary pipe bombs were found at the homes of former Presidents Obama and Clinton as well as in CNN’s Midtown newsroom. More explosive devices have been mailed in recent days to the home of Democratic mega-donor George Soros and to the offices of Reps. Maxine Waters (D-Calif.) and Debbie Wasserman Schultz (D-Fla.).

“We’re extremely angry, upset, unhappy about what we witnessed this morning,” said Trump, who has a long history of attacking and peddling false conspiracy theories about CNN, Soros, the Clintons and Obama.

The mail bombs came after an extraordinarily aggressive week for Trump, during which he has made baseless assertions about “unknown Middle Easterners” marching on the U.S. southern border while billing himself a “nationalist” and calling Democrats an “angry mob.”

It was not immediately known who’s responsible for the explosives, but even some Republicans acknowledged Trump needs to temper his rhetoric.

“Everyone, Democrats and Republicans, should tone it down," Rep. Pete King (R-N.Y.) told the Daily News. "There’s a hostile climate out there."

King urged Trump to continue the conversation in a bipartisan manner.

“In the next few days, he should find a way to discuss it,” King said. “I would try to have an old statesman or a person from the Democratic Party help him do this.”

Local leaders also took subtle shots at Trump.

“This atmosphere of hatred is contributing to the choices people are making to turn to violence,” Mayor de Blasio said at a press conference outside CNN’s headquarters. “The way to stop that is to turn back the other way, to bring down the temperature, to end any messages about the use of violence against people we disagree with. And that has to start at the top.”
